# Project Demonstration

## Overview

The Project Demonstration showcases the complete functionality of OptiCrop by presenting how users interact with the system from registration to crop prediction. The demonstration highlights the integration of the frontend, backend, Machine Learning model, and database, proving that the application operates as a complete and functional smart agriculture solution.

---

# Demonstration Objectives

The project demonstration aims to:

- Present the complete working of OptiCrop.
- Show the interaction between different system modules.
- Demonstrate accurate crop prediction.
- Verify smooth communication between the frontend, backend, and database.
- Highlight the practical benefits of the application.

---

# Demonstration Environment

The project was demonstrated using the following environment:

| Component | Technology |
|-----------|------------|
| Frontend | React.js |
| Backend | Flask |
| Database | MongoDB |
| Machine Learning | Scikit-learn |
| Development Tool | Visual Studio Code |
| Version Control | Git & GitHub |

---

# Demonstration Workflow

The demonstration follows the complete user journey through the application.

### Step 1 – User Login

The user logs into the application using valid credentials. New users can register before accessing the system.

---

### Step 2 – Enter Agricultural Parameters

The user enters the required values:

- Nitrogen (N)
- Phosphorus (P)
- Potassium (K)
- Temperature
- Humidity
- Soil pH
- Rainfall

The application validates the inputs before processing them.

---

### Step 3 – Crop Prediction

After submitting the data, the Machine Learning model analyzes the inputs and predicts the most suitable crop based on the trained dataset.

---

### Step 4 – Display Result

The application displays:

- Recommended Crop
- Prediction Summary
- Entered Input Values

The result is presented in a clear and easy-to-understand format.

---

### Step 5 – Save Prediction

The generated prediction is stored in the MongoDB database, allowing users to access their prediction history later.

---

### Step 6 – Submit Feedback

Users can provide feedback about the prediction, helping improve future versions of the application.

